I think Dale is right. I&#39;ve done a fair share of Swing-JUnit-Tes=
ts and your
code ought not work. The usual JUnit-Runner will run the tests =
in a &quot;normal&quot;
Thread, while UI-Manipulation, including Frame creation, shou=
ld be done in
the AWT Eventqueue, even in a test. Also, if you interact wit=
h your GUI you
need to wait for the events that you dispatch to be processe=
d. Abbot, a ui
test framework like FEST, provides a wait() method for that,=
 which uses the
invokeAndWait()-Method mentioned by Dale with an empty Runn=
able.

